        199
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Using Azure Storage with a Hudson Continuous Integration solution",
      "pos": [
        513,
        578
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        581,
        632
      ],
      "content": "By <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Microsoft Open Technologies Inc.<ept id=\"p1\">][ms-open-tech]</ept>"
    },
    {
      "content": "Overview",
      "pos": [
        638,
        646
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following information shows how to use the Azure Blob service as a repository of build artifacts created by a Hudson Continuous Integration (CI) solution, or as a source of downloadable files to be used in a build process.",
      "pos": [
        648,
        874
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "One of the scenarios where you would find this useful is when you're coding in an agile development environment (using Java or other languages), builds are running based on continuous integration, and you need a repository for your build artifacts, so that you could, for example, share them with other organization members, your customers, or maintain an archive.",
      "pos": [
        875,
        1239
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Another scenario is when your build job itself requires other files, for example, dependencies to download as part of the build input.",
      "pos": [
        1241,
        1375
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this tutorial you will be using the Azure Storage Plugin for Hudson CI made available by Microsoft Open Technologies, Inc.",
      "pos": [
        1377,
        1502
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Introduction to Hudson",
      "pos": [
        1507,
        1529
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Hudson enables continuous integration of a software project by allowing developers to easily integrate their code changes and have builds produced automatically and frequently, thereby increasing the productivity of the developers.",
      "pos": [
        1533,
        1764
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Builds are versioned, and build artifacts can be uploaded to various repositories.",
      "pos": [
        1765,
        1847
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This topic will show how to use Azure blob storage as the repository of the build artifacts.",
      "pos": [
        1848,
        1940
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It will also show how to download dependencies from Azure blob storage.",
      "pos": [
        1941,
        2012
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        2014,
        2076
      ],
      "content": "More information about Hudson can be found at <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Meet Hudson<ept id=\"p1\">][]</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "Benefits of using the Blob service",
      "pos": [
        2081,
        2115
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Benefits of using the Blob service to host your agile development build artifacts include:",
      "pos": [
        2120,
        2210
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "High availability of your build artifacts and/or downloadable dependencies.",
      "pos": [
        2214,
        2289
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Performance when your Hudson CI solution uploads your build artifacts.",
      "pos": [
        2292,
        2362
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Performance when your customers and partners download your build artifacts.",
      "pos": [
        2365,
        2440
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Control over user access policies, with a choice between anonymous access, expiration-based shared access signature access, private access, etc.",
      "pos": [
        2443,
        2587
      ]
    },
    {
